To the little girl who started wearing a bra at 9 and subsequently started wearing her brother’s tshirts to hide, to the girl who hated when adult men and women would make comments on her new developing body, to the girl who loved to draw others in attempt to capture their idiosyncrasies- the quiet things she’d wish others found beautiful within her not just what she looked like, to the little girl who grew up to be a little woman- shorter than the other models around her, to the girl who never wore a bikini from the ages of 10 to 22 because she was ashamed of her big hips, her stretch marks, her soft tummy, her full chest, her inability to see herself worthy of love- you don’t have to hide anymore. We are all worthy of love, respect, and the courage to chase our dreams. If you would’ve told that same little girl that someday she would be walking runway alongside some of the loveliest ladies wearing incredible women owned brands and with the @nyknicks . I bet she wouldn’t have even believed you. That shows how far we’ve come, but we still have so much further to go. Don’t just chase your dreams, “cat”walk directly towards them and claim what’s yours, because every body is beautiful and this world is subject to constant change. I model because it’s my hope to help the industry become a more empathetic and inclusive space, and more importantly be a role model to little girls who might feel just as I did. A girl with courage and a big vision, a girl who deserved the hug she always wanted someone to give her, a girl who never saw models that looked like her, a girl who loves her body for its strength to carry her massive heart, the girl who always knew the heart is just a muscle - it gets stronger the more we use it. Thank you for having me @glambaefashion @asdesign2020 @unleashedsummit @vbryant_ @thegarden @nyknicks and thank you for being the incredible women that you are. 🏀📸

Oh the transformative powers of makeup. No I do not wake-up studio ready, but I still love the girl I see in the mirror each morning. Makeup just like skincare or working out or meditation/ self reflection can be a form of self care, I’ve always found it relaxing. I don’t usually get to wear it unless I’m shooting, but when I do it feels so empowering. Makeup is fun because it’s like wearing a costume on any given day of the year. There is a real power in taking it all off and still loving the person underneath. To all the makeup artists and stylists who transform us models into the glamorous people you see in photos - you guys pour your heart and souls into your craft and I have so much endless respect for you. ❤️

“I am not what has happened to me, I am who I choose to become”
#metoo 
Our industry needs to change, our justice system needs to empathize, our voices need to be heard, our 
bodies are ours only. My story is very personal and private to me, I’ve not found the strength to become public with it and I may never feel comfortable doing so. But Im treating my mind and body with grace in the wake of trauma, everyday is a new day and time is a construct, but the bravery to keep waking up each morning and find a way to still love your self? heals. My support system is everything, those who I have confided in- a list of those I know really care, a list of which I always remember to place myself on as well. Thank you to the women who have reminded me that it is okay to not come forward yet, that healing isn’t a linear timeline and days, months and years don’t equate to a reversal of time, there’s no way to have stopped what happened to you. There is no way to go back in time and save yourself from what you have endured. There is only a path ahead, healing isn’t a street you cross, it’s a long road you take. There are more incredible people in this industry than predators, and just because someone says they love you doesn’t mean you can trust them. If you are working, living, friends or family, or in a relationship someone who has hurt you, please know you did nothing wrong in trusting them. It is not your fault. If any of you reading this have been sexually assaulted and not ready to come forward, I encourage you to tell just one friend. Have even just one singular person in your corner, to advocate for you. If you can’t, there are many anonymous call centers like @rainn ready and hoping to help you and set you up with the care you need. You can also send me a message if you feel alone, because I have been there. Thank you to my dear friends, my doctors and my advocates for carrying me back to myself all this time. I love you all, be kind to one another. Thank you. 
If you’d like to help in a small way, I’ve attached a donation link to support “Rainn” a victim’s national hotline for abuse survivors.
@modelallianceny @rainn

My agent recommended I take more selfies so here’s 3 instagram, eat your heart out. In good news, I’ve been off prednisone for 5 weeks and my face is no longer swollen like a balloon 🌝 the way it’s been since last October but increasingly inflated 🎈lol🫣 yay- not. Autoimmune disorders are no fun. I’ve struggled with chronic hypothyroid disease and pcos since I was a teen, the fatigue, the random but rapid weight gain, untreatable depression, bad anemia, always freezing, hormonal fluctuations, terrible period pain, these are just a few of the long list of ways your body might be telling you there is an underlying problem. While it’s not curable and you’ll always be up and down, modern medicine can definitely help alleviate some of these issues, and get you back feeling like your healthy self again. If anyone is struggling with an autoimmune problem, I see you, hear you, and stand with you. ❤️‍🩹

Dear instagram,
Tomorrow I go in for my first surgery at @memorialsloankettering cancer center. I’ve been pretty quiet about my health because of it’s uncertainty, and because I’m shy and don’t like sharing aspects about my personal life with the entire world, but with the more serious issues I feel it’s important to at least acknowledge their existence. I also don’t want this affecting my career in a negative way, though I may have some new scars around my abdomen that I didn’t have before. (Im a tough 🍪 so please don’t feel bad for me- can handle it) While this has been a very scary past two months I’m excited to come out on the other side of it stronger than ever. I’m so grateful to have such an incredible medical team taking care of me, and for my friends and family. Continuously throughout my life, I’ve been taught life is far too short and precious to waste. This experience has really taught me to be kinder to my body and to start showing it love instead of hate, there’s only so much control we have over our lives. There is so much pressure to look Iike the “perfect woman,” so much work to be considered attractive and maintain this desirability- it’s exhausting, I’d much rather be authentic and honest about my body. We stretch ourselves too thin, and yet we still come up short- it’s never going to be enough. Sometimes life throws unexpected wrenches in our plans, and we have no other choice but to accept them and keep pushing through. Hopefully, emerging a woman with more grace, empathy and understanding - three things I think are far more beautiful than any perfect body will ever be. That being said, I’m going to be taking a few weeks to recover and I look forward to working with everyone again soon! 
With so much love, Katie ❤️
